Headlines.Author: Sarah Sloat
Headlines.Headline: Five German Breweries Face Hefty Fines in Price-Fixing Probe

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Sarah Sloat Five breweries in Germany, Europe's biggest beer producer, face millions in fines after the country's antitrust authority said Monday they had colluded to fix prices between 2006 and 2008. The Federal Cartel Office will impose fines totaling 106.5 million euros ($145.6 million) on Bitburger Braugruppe, Krombacher Brauerei, Veltins, Warsteiner, and Privatbrauerei Ernst Barre, along with seven individuals connected to the breweries. Anheuser-Busch InBev, the world's largest brewer by sales, was exempted from penalties because a German unit brought the collusion to light, the cartel office said.

Headlines.Author: Anthony Harrup
Headlines.Headline: Mexico's January-September Foreign Direct Investment $28.2 Billion

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Anthony Harrup MEXICO CITY--Foreign direct investment in Mexico more than doubled in the first nine months of the year, boosted by brewer Anheuser-Busch Inbev N.V.'s (BUD, ABI.BT ) buyout of Mexican beer maker Grupo Modelo SAB, the Economy Ministry said Thursday. Foreign direct investment in the January-September period totaled $28.2 billion, compared with $13 billion for the first nine months of 2012. Excluding the Modelo sale, FDI was up 15% at $15 billion, the ministry added. Third-quarter FDI amounted to $3.4 billion.

Headlines.Author: Inti Landauro
Headlines.Headline: InBev 3Q Net Profit Rises 20% to $2.21B Despite Brazil Weakness

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Inti Landauro and Peter Evans PARIS--Anheuser-Busch InBev N.V. BUD Thursday said net profit grew even as weakness in Brazil continued to be a concern for the world's largest brewer by revenue. The maker of Budweiser and Stella Artois reported a third-quarter net profit of $2.21 billion, up from $1.84 billion a year earlier. Revenue increased 3% to $11.73 billion. After years of soar-away growth in Brazil, AB InBev's second-biggest market, a tough consumer economy is denting sales. Third-quarter volumes in Brazil fell 5%, compared with a growth of 0.2% last year.

Headlines.Headline: SABMiller Continues Legal Battle Over Beer Deals in Mexico

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Amy Guthrie MEXICO CITY--SABMiller PLC (SAB.LN, SBMRY), the world's second-largest brewer by sales, said Wednesday that a Mexican federal court has accepted its case to consider overruling a July antitrust settlement on exclusive sales agreements that SABMiller believes "failed to truly address the monopolistic activities" in the Mexican beer market. Mexico's Federal Competition Commission stopped short of prohibiting the beer contracts entirely, reaching an agreement with top brewers Anheuser-Busch InBev NV's BUD Grupo Modelo unit and Heineken NV's (HEIA.AE, HEINY) Cerveceria Cuauhtemoc Moctezuma to limit their use of exclusivity contracts at small shops and some other points of sale, such as restaurants.

Headlines.Author: Amy Guthrie
Headlines.Headline: SABMiller: Mexico Antitrust Beer Ruling 'Did Not Go Far Enough'

PARAGRAPH.#text: --AB InBev, Heineken operate virtual duopoly in Mexico --Mexico is the world's fifth-biggest beer market --SABMiller studying options after settlement By Amy Guthrie MEXICO CITY--SABMiller PLC (SAB.LN, SBMRY), the world's second-largest brewer by sales, said Friday the resolution on the use of sales exclusivities in the large Mexican beer market "did not go far enough" to materially change conditions for access and really stoke competition. Mexico's Federal Competition Commission stopped short of prohibiting the contracts entirely, reaching an agreement with top brewers Anheuser-Busch InBev NV's BUD Grupo Modelo unit and Heineken NV's (HEIA.AE, HEINY) Cerveceria Cuauhtemoc Moctezuma to limit their use of exclusivity contracts to 25% of points of sale, and to reduce that number to 20% within five years.

PARAGRAPH.#text: --Mexican anti-trust authority caps brewers' exclusivity deals --Ruling impacts world's fifth-biggest beer market --AB InBev, Heineken account for almost all beer sales in Mexico (Updates with official statements from Mexican anti-trust authority, Heineken) By Amy Guthrie MEXICO CITY--Mexico's top brewers have reached an agreement with the country's anti-trust authority to limit their sales exclusivity contracts with corner stores, bars and restaurants, allowing more elbow room for craft brewers and other players in a lucrative market split by Anheuser-Busch InBev N.V.'s BUD Grupo Modelo unit and Heineken NV's (HEIA.AE) Cerveceria Cuauhtemoc Moctezuma.

Headlines.Author: Amy Guthrie
Headlines.Headline: Top Mexican Brewer Modelo Agrees to Limit Exclusivity Deals

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Amy Guthrie MEXICO CITY--Mexico's top brewer said Thursday it reached an agreement with the country's anti-trust authority to limit its sales exclusivity contracts with corner stores, bars and restaurants, allowing more room for craft brewers and other players in a lucrative market split by Anheuser-Busch InBev N.V.'s BUD Grupo Modelo unit and Heineken N.V.'s (HEIA.AE) Cerveceria Cuauhtemoc Moctezuma. Modelo said in a statement it would cap such agreements to no more than 25% of its points of sale, with the aim of reducing that number to 20% by 2018.

Headlines.Headline: AB InBev Shuts Russian Brewery; Blames Increased Taxes, Regulation

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Lukas I. Alpert MOSCOW--Beer giant Anheuser-Busch InBev (ABI.BT) said Tuesday it is closing a brewery in Russia, blaming high taxes and increased regulation for driving down production across the country. The company's Russian unit, SUN InBev, said it would relocate production from the Novocheboksarsk brewery in Chuvashia to its seven other sites in Russia. Opened in 2001, the factory produces Stella Artois, Staropramen, Brahma, Lowenbrau and Siberian Corona. "Unfortunately we do not see any other option in the current beer market conditions.

U.S. jobless claims dropped by 27,000 to 341,000 in the week ended Feb. 9, according to the Labor Department. Economists surveyed by MarketWatch expected a much smaller drop. "Overall the feel is that the labor market is improving as evidenced by a dip in the number of insured claims amongst claimants, which eased to 2.4% from 2.5%," said Andrew Wilkinson, chief economic strategist at Miller Tabak, in emailed comments.

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Simon Zekaria LONDON--SABMiller PLC (SAB.LN) Thursday warned of slowing economic growth in some of its markets, but still posted higher profit and revenue. "Broad-based revenue and profit growth in the first half reflects the continued success of our approach," said Chief Executive Graham Mackay. Robust demand in emerging economies--which account for over two-thirds of the company's earnings--has supported SABMiller, as well as lower operational exposure than rivals to the recession-hit European markets.

Headlines.Headline: Mexican Antitrust Authority Approves AB InBev Buy of Modelo

PARAGRAPH.#text: MEXICO CITY--Mexico's antitrust authority has approved Anheuser-Busch InBev SA/NV's (ABI, BUD) purchase of Mexican brewer Grupo Modelo SA (GMODELO.MX), Modelo said Thursday. The approval is one of many conditions that the deal must receive to be consummated, the brewer said in a filing with the Mexican Stock Exchange. Modelo agreed in June to sell AB InBev the 50% of Modelo that AB InBev didn't already own, in a deal valued at $20.1 billion. Modelo roughly splits the domestic market for beer sales in Mexico with Dutch brewer Heineken NV (HINKY), which bought Mexican brewer Femsa SAB's (FEMSA.MX, FMX) beer business in 2010.

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Simon Zekaria LONDON--Anheuser Busch-InBev NV (ABI.BT), the world's largest brewer by revenue, Wednesday said net profit grew as it benefited from an ongoing recovery in North America and solid trading in Brazil, but global demand continued to slacken. Third-quarter net profit rose to $1.84 billion from $1.59 billion a year earlier, missing analysts' forecast of $2.04 billion. The brewer's earnings before interest, taxes, amortization and depreciation rose to $3.98 billion from $3.97 billion, also falling short of a $4.06 billion forecast.

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Simon Zekaria LONDON--SABMiller PLC (SAB.LN) Thursday posted a rise in revenue as it benefited from high exposure to fast-growing markets, but the brewing giant flagged slowing demand in its key region of Latin America. Robust volume growth in emerging economies, which account for about 70% of the company's earnings, has supported the world's No. 2 brewer by sales after Anheuser-Busch InBev NV (ABI.BT). The U.K.-based giant also has lower exposure to sluggish trading in recession-hit Western markets than its rivals, such as Heineken NV ( HEIA.AE) and Carlsberg A/S (CARL-A.KO), which have suffered from lower consumer spending, higher unemployment and a shift towards premium spirits from mainstream beer.

Headlines.Author: Amy Guthrie
Headlines.Headline: Modelo Lured by AB InBev's Size as Beer Industry Consolidates

PARAGRAPH.#text: --Modelo CEO viewed full sale to beer giant as best value proposition --AB InBev CEO calls purchase "natural next step" in relationship --Room to grow Corona brand sales, accomplish more together By Amy Guthrie MEXICO CITY--The chief executive of Mexican brewer Grupo Modelo SAB (GMODELO.MX) said Friday that his company just couldn't pass on the opportunity to be fully integrated with the biggest and strongest beer maker in the world. By selling to Anheuser-Busch InBev NV BUD the 50% of Modelo that AB InBev didn't already own, in a deal valued at $20.1 billion, Modelo is firmly positioning itself as a "world leader" amid further beer industry consolidation, Carlos Fernandez told reporters during a conference call.

Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Ledger: Judgment Time for Health Care
Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: Judgment Time for Health Care

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Hope you all had a restful weekend because we're heading into a huge week with the future of U.S. heath-care policy and possibly the fate of the euro hanging in the balance.
Fortunately, we've got some of the world's sharpest big-company CFOs gathered together in Washington D.C. at the second annual Wall Street Journal CFO Network meeting, along with a set of first-rate experts and policy players to help us make sense of it all. This year's program features IASB Chairman Hans Hoogervorst on global accounting rules, IMF Chief Economist Olivier Blanchard and UBS Chairman Axel Weber on the crisis in Europe, and House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Dave Camp on paying for everything we want.

Headlines.Author: Melodie Warner
Headlines.Headline: Anheuser-Busch InBev To Invest $1Bln+ In US Plants Through 2014

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Anheuser-Busch InBev N.V. (BUD, ABI.BT) plans to invest more than $1 billion in its U.S. breweries and other facilities through 2014 to spur growth in its largest market. The brewer of Budweiser and Bud Light beers plans to further modernize brewing processes, upgrade systems to reduce greenhouse-gas emissions, and install equipment for new products and innovations, among other things. In addition to its breweries, Anheuser-Busch plans to invest in its agricultural operations, such as $40 million spent earlier this year to rebrick the furnace and expand production capacity at its Longhorn Glass facility in Houston.

Headlines.Author: Simon Zekaria

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Simon Zekaria Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES LONDON (Dow Jones)--SABMiller PLC SBMRY, maker of Miller Lite, Grolsch and Peroni Nastro Azzuro, Wednesday said it has agreed to acquire iconic Australian peer Foster's Group Ltd. PARAGRAPH.#text: By Matthew Dalton Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES BRUSSELS (Dow Jones)--Anheuser-Busch InBev (ABI.BT), the world's largest brewer, Thursday posted a 26% rise in second-quarter net profit, buoyed by cost-cutting in the U.S. and price increases in Brazil. But sales in the U.S., its largest market, suffered from high gas prices and bad weather, AB InBev said. That, and efforts to raise prices for its cheapest beers, lead to a 1.9% drop in North American sales volumes in the three months to end-June. Brazil, normally the driver of AB InBev's sales growth, disappointed slightly.

Headlines.Author: Maxwell Murphy
Headlines.Headline: Molson Coors Profit Off Despite Higher MillerCoors Profit

PARAGRAPH.#text: --Unemployment a bigger driver of lower volume than other economic worries --CEO declines comment on rumors it is interested in Foster's (Updates with details and interview with CEO throughout.) NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Molson Coors Brewing Co.'s TAP second-quarter earnings fell 6.1% as the brewer was hurt by lower sales volume and rising commodities costs as it struggles with high unemployment that crimped beer consumption in its largest markets. The beer maker's board authorized a new stock repurchase program for up to $1.2 billion of the company's Class B stock over three years, another in a slew of companies to use buybacks or dividends to return cash to shareholders amid economic weakness.

Headlines.Author: Strong Volumes
Headlines.Headline: SABMiller Sales Boosted By Strong Volumes In Asia, Africa

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Simon Zekaria Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES LONDON (Dow Jones)--SABMiller PLC SBMRY, the FTSE 100 brewer pursuing a multi-billion dollar takeover of Australia's Foster's Group Ltd. (FGL.AU), Thursday posted a rise in first-quarter sales on higher volumes, driven by robust demand in emerging markets. SABMiller, the world's second-biggest brewer by volume after Anheuser-Busch InBev NV (ABI.BT), benefited from a strong performance in Asia and Africa, where socio-economic improvement, rising incomes and a thirst for Western lifestyles are fuelling consumption.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: SABMiller Sales Boosted By Strong Volumes In Asia, Africa

Headlines.Author: Tom Murphy
Headlines.Headline: Big Brewers Size Up Brazil's Schincariol

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Tom Murphy Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES SAO PAULO (Dow Jones)--Brazil's burgeoning beer market, long dominated by the Brazilian unit of global brewing giant Anheuser-Busch InBev, could use some competition, and global brewers could use faster sales growth outside mature markets like the U.S. The answer to both problems, say industry analysts, could be a small, family-run Brazilian brewer with a funny name: Schincariol (pronounced SKIN-kah-ree-ALL). "To find growth, the big global players have to look to emerging markets, and beer sales in Brazil are booming," said Renato Prado, an analyst at Sao Paulo's Fator brokerage.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Big Brewers Size Up Brazil's Schincariol

PARAGRAPH.#text: (Updates with preliminary pricing guidance in the third paragraph, outstanding bond level in the fourth paragraph and no comment from company in sixth paragraph) NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Anheuser-Busch InBev (ABI.BT) announced a benchmark-sized two-part debt offering on Thursday. The senior unsecured issue will include three-year fixed- and floating-rate notes and is expected to be sold later Thursday via active bookrunners Barclays Capital, Bank of America Merrill Lynch (BAC), Deutsche Bank (DB), Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS) and Societe Generale (SCGLY).

Headlines.Author: Ken Parks
Headlines.Headline: Argentina Unit Of AB Inbev To Invest ARS3 Bln Under 5-Year Plan

PARAGRAPH.#text: BUENOS AIRES (Dow Jones)--The Argentine arm of global brewing giant Anheuser-Busch InBev NV (ABI.BT, BUD) will invest 3 billion pesos ($730 million) during a five-year period. The investment will go to increasing the company's output, modernizing its bottling plants, and strengthening its distribution network, according to a statement published Wednesday by Argentina's Office of the Presidency. The announcement followed a meeting that same day between President Cristina Kirchner and executives of Cerveceria y Malteria Quilmes.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Argentina Unit Of AB Inbev To Invest ARS3 Bln Under 5-Year Plan

Headlines.Author: Kellie Geressy-Nilsen

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Kellie Geressy-Nilsen NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Anheuser-Busch InBev (ABI.BT) has a benchmark-sized three-year debt offering on tap Thursday. The senior unsecured issue will include three-year fixed- and/or floating-rate notes and is expected to be sold later this session via active bookrunners Barclays Capital, Bank of America Merrill Lynch (BAC), Deutsche Bank (DB), Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS) and Societe Generale. Proceeds will be used for general corporate purposes, which could include the repayment of outstanding debt securities.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Anheuser-Busch Prepping Benchmark-Sized 3-Year Debt Offering

Headlines.Headline: Judge Rules Against Molson Coors in NHL Sponsorship Spat -Report

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES A Canadian judge on Friday put Molson Coors Brewing Co.'s TAP sponsorship deal with the National Hockey League in doubt after ruling the league had reneged on an existing deal with Labatt Breweries, according to the Toronto Star. The Ontario Superior Court ruled for Labatt, which claimed it already had a Canadian sponsorship agreement in place with the NHL before Molson Coors signed its seven-year North American sponsorship pact in February, the paper said. Labatt said in February that it negotiated a "good faith" contract extension through 2014, The Wall Street Journal reported at the time.

PARAGRAPH.#text: (recasts, adds detail throughout) By Cynthia Koons Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES MELBOURNE (Dow Jones)--Australian brewing giant Foster's Group Ltd. (FGL.AU) said Friday it had nothing to disclose in regard to a potential buyout of the brewer after media reports indicated bidders were beginning to circle. Foster's shares were up 5.1% earlier in the trading session, prompting the Australian Stock Exchange to inquire about the stock's rising price. PARAGRAPH.#text: By William Mauldin and Anna Marij van der Meulen Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES MOSCOW(Dow Jones)--Russian lawmakers this week said they would look to tighten the way beer is regulated, which could hurt international brewers such as Carlsberg A/s (CARL-A.KO), Heineken N.V. (HEIA.AE) and Anheuser-Busch InBev (ABI.BT). The bill, which is in the early stages of discussion in Russia's lower house of parliament, the Duma, could limit the sale of beer near certain places such as schools and stadiums. The legislators, taking their cue from Prime Minister Vladimir Putin's government, are considering treating beer in the same way as wine and liquor whose sale is banned in certain locations and at certain times of day in Moscow and other cities, as they try to cut down on alcoholism and underage drinking.

Headlines.Author: Ben Dummett
Headlines.Headline: 2ND  Anheuser-Busch Raises C$600M From Debt Issue

PARAGRAPH.#text: (Adds details about size and pricing in first three paragraphs.) TORONTO (Dow Jones)--Anheuser-Busch InBev Worldwide Inc. a unit of Belgium-based beer maker Anheuser-Busch InBev N.V. BUD, raised C$600 million from an issue of bonds maturing in January 2016, marking the first time the company is tapping the Canadian new-issue debt market, according to person familiar with the matter. The minimum amount targeted was C$500 million. The issue was priced at 113 basis points over the relevant government of Canada benchmark, or at the low end of the guidance, to yield 3.658%.

Headlines.Author: Don Curren
Headlines.Headline: Canada Bonds Lower But Outperform US Treasurys

PARAGRAPH.#text: TORONTO (Dow Jones)-Canadian bonds ended mostly lower Wednesday, taking direction from the sharp selloff in U.S. Treasurys but continuing to outperform that market. Canada's two-year bond yield was at 1.671% late Wednesday, from 1.615% late Tuesday. The 10-year bond yield was at 3.240%, from 3.239%, marking its highest level since July. Bond yields move inversely to their prices. The spread between the Canadian 10-year yield and its U.S. equivalent narrowed to four basis points on Wednesday from nine on Tuesday and 32 one month ago.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Canada Bonds Lower But Outperform US Treasurys

PARAGRAPH.#text: NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Emerging market debt weakened Monday, tracking a mostly weaker day for U.S. stocks on renewed concerns over Europe's sovereign-debt problems. Investors also made room for a flurry of new bond issuance as borrowers continued to take advantage of ample liquidity and lower yields. The securities, which will mature in November 2015, are expected to yield between 10% and 10.125%, according to a fund manager's term sheet seen by Dow Jones Newswires. The notes are linked to the real but payments are made in dollars. The size of the deal has not yet been finalized.

Headlines.Author: Simon Kennedy
Headlines.Headline: EUROPE MARKETS: European Stocks Fall Ahead Of Fed Decision

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Simon Kennedy European stocks ended lower Wednesday as jitters prevailed ahead of a monetary-policy announcement by the U.S. Federal Reserve. The Stoxx Europe 600 index  fell 0.4% to finish at 266.51. After the close of European markets on Wednesday, the Fed is widely expected to announce another round of quantitative easing in an effort to buoy the sluggish American economy and tackle persistently high unemployment. Economists expect the Fed to buy between $500 billion and $750 billion of government bonds and say the impact of purchases around that level are already priced into markets.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: EUROPE MARKETS: European Stocks Fall Ahead Of Fed Decision

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Barbara Kollmeyer U.S. stock futures were slightly higher on Wednesday after the Republican Party won control of the House of Representatives and as investors awaited the outcome of the Federal Reserve meeting. Futures for the Dow Jones Industrial Average gained 12 points to 11164 and the S&P 500 index added 0.9 point to 1193.60. Futures for the Nasdaq 100 index edged up 0.75 points to 2151. PARAGRAPH.#text: Anheuser-Busch InBev lost a long, bitter court battle with a Czech brewer over the name of its flagship brand when the European Court of Justice  ruled Thursday that it may not register "Budweiser" as a trademark in the European Union.

Headlines.Author: Peppi Kiviniemi
Headlines.Headline: AB-InBev Can't Register Budweiser Trademark EU-Wide-Top Court

PARAGRAPH.#text: (Adds detail, AB-InBev comment) By Peppi Kiviniemi Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES BRUSSELS (Dow Jones)--Anheuser-Busch InBev (ABI.BT) won't be allowed to register its Budweiser beer brand as a European Union wide trademark after Europe's highest court rejected the beer giant's appeal Thursday. This comes as a final blow in AB-InBev's decades-long battle with Czech competitor Budejovicky Budvar NP to gain control of the Budweiser name in Europe. AB-InBev had appealed for the European Court of Justice to overturn an earlier decision by the European General Court--which refused AB-InBev permission to register the Budweiser brand as its trademark--due to clashes with existing trademark protection Budvar already enjoyed.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: AB-InBev Can't Register Budweiser Trademark EU-Wide-Top Court

PARAGRAPH.#text: (Rewrites, adds analyst's comments.) Danish brewer Carlsberg A/S (CARL-A.KO) Tuesday said first quarter operating profit fell 6.7%, beating market expectations, as margins improved in a number of key regions. The maker of Tuborg, Carlsberg and Kronenbourg beer said operating profit, the measure most closely watched by analysts, fell to DKK735 million ($126 million) from DKK788 million a year earlier, but well ahead of market expectations for DKK533 million. Strong margin improvement in Northern and Western Europe and Asia was to some extent offset by an expected margin weakness in Eastern Europe following a significant Russian excise tax increase, the company said.

Headlines.Author: Matthew Dalton

PARAGRAPH.#text: (Adds analyst comment.) BRUSSELS (Dow Jones)--Anheuser-Busch InBev N.V. (ABI.BT), the world's largest brewer, Wednesday said its first-quarter net profit fell 34%, as extremely strong sales growth in Brazil was offset by a one-time charge taken to refinance the debt it used to buy Anheuser-Busch in 2008. Net profit was $475 million for the quarter, down from $716 million a year ago, and below analysts' expectations of $847 million. The brewer, which makes Budweiser, Bud Light and Stella Artois, booked a financing charge of $419 million in the quarter, accounting for the large miss.

PARAGRAPH.#text: NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--The British are coming. So are the Japanese, Irish, Spanish and Dutch. Foreign countries and companies are issuing dollar-denominated debt--frequently called Yankee bonds--at a record pace this winter, tapping the world's most liquid market after being banished to the sidelines for much of last year. PARAGRAPH.#text: (Re-writes, adds CEO comment.) LONDON (Dow Jones)--Brewer SABMiller PLC (SAB.LN) said Thursday that, while tough trading conditions will continue in the second half of its financial year, the outlook is starting to improve, and it stands to benefit from favorable currency exchange and the easing of cost pressures. The world's second-biggest brewer by volume after Anheuser-Busch Inbev NV (ABI.BT) said sales in the six months to end-September fell 20.8% to $8.85 billion from $11.17 billion. Net profit dropped to $973 million from $1.42 billion, hit by high input costs and adverse foreign-exchange rates.

PARAGRAPH.#text: (Adds detail.) LONDON (Dow Jones)--Brewer SABMiller PLC (SAB.LN) Thursday posted a 6% rise in adjusted first-half earnings and said that while tough trading conditions will continue in the second half of the year it should benefit from easing currency and cost pressures. The London-based company--which counts Grolsch, Peroni Nastro Azzurro, Castle Lager and Pilsner Urquell among its brands--said earnings per share before exceptional items in the six months to Sept. 30 rose 6% to 80 cents, up from 75.2 cents a year ago, and ahead of expectations.

PARAGRAPH.#text: (Adds AB InBev reaction, detail.) LUXEMBOURG (Dow Jones)--Europe's highest court Tuesday issued a ruling that could end attempts by Czech state brewer Budejovicky Budvar to stop Belgian beer giant Anheuser-Busch InBev (ABI.BT) - the brewer of the iconic Budweiser brand - using the brand name "Bud" in Austria. It could also open the doors for AB InBev to challenge Budvar's trademarks in other countries. Budvar, which has brewed Czech Budweiser beer since 1895, has registered the "Bud" or "Budweiser" trademarks in 37 countries, including Austria.

Among the companies whose shares are actively trading in the session are CardioNet Inc. (BEAT), Oshkosh Corp. (OSK) and Force Protection Inc. (FRPT).

Headlines.BodyHeadline: US HOT STOCKS: CardioNet, Oshkosh, Force Protection

Headlines.Headline: Wyeth to Join S&P 500

PARAGRAPH.#text: Standard & Poor's said drug maker Wyeth will replace Anheuser-Busch Cos. in the S&P 500-stock index, while Life Technologies Corp. will replace Applied Biosystems Inc.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Wyeth to Join S&P 500
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Anjali Cordeiro
Headlines.Headline: Anheuser Shares Continue Slide

PARAGRAPH.#text: Anheuser-Busch shares fell further Friday and traded nearly 20% below the proposed price of the InBev acquisition. InBev said it was committed to the acquisition at the agreed-upon terms.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Anheuser Shares Continue Slide
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Heidi N. Moore
Headlines.Headline: Bankers Follow Wisdom of Zen

PARAGRAPH.#text: Zen philosophers remind their students that they can't see their reflections in rushing water. Instead, they must be still.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Bankers Follow Wisdom of Zen
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Matthew Karnitschnig
Headlines.Headline: Modelo Would Buy Back Anheuser Stake

PARAGRAPH.#text: Modelo is seeking to buy back all or part of the 50% stake Anheuser-Busch holds in the Mexican brewer, which would alter InBev's pending purchase of Anheuser.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Modelo Would Buy Back Anheuser Stake
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: David Kesmodel
Headlines.Headline: InBev Postpones Rights Offering

PARAGRAPH.#text: Belgian beer titan InBev said it was delaying plans to raise new equity to help fund its $52 billion acquisition of Anheuser-Busch citing "unprecedented volatility" in capital markets.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: InBev Postpones Rights Offering
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Gregory Zuckerman
Headlines.Headline: Field Opens for M&A Risk-Takers

PARAGRAPH.#text: Merger arbitragers are on the run. That is presenting ripe opportunities for investors itching to play the M&A game.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Field Opens for M&A Risk-Takers
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: U.S. Stocks Fall as Cheer for Rescue Wanes

PARAGRAPH.#text: U.S. stocks turned lower as initial enthusiasm for the government's moves to prop up Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac gave way to concern about the plan's details and pain yet to come from the broader credit crunch.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: U.S. Stocks Fall as Cheer for Rescue Wanes

Headlines.Author: Julie Jargon
Headlines.Headline: Anheuser Sees Charge From Buyouts

PARAGRAPH.#text: Anheuser forecast a charge of up to $400 million from an early-retirement program and intends to cut pension and health benefits.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Anheuser Sees Charge From Buyouts
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: David Kesmodel
Headlines.Headline: Anheuser Plans Job Cuts

PARAGRAPH.#text: Anheuser-Busch said it planned to slash about 1,000 jobs, raise beer prices and buy back more of its shares, setting a new business plan after rebuffing InBev's unsolicited bid.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Anheuser Plans Job Cuts
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Susan Murdoch
Headlines.Headline: Foster's Wine Review Leads to Takeover Talk

PARAGRAPH.#text: Foster's could be split up or taken over, now that management has begun a strategic review of the brewer's wine business.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Foster's Wine Review Leads to Takeover Talk

Headlines.Author: Matthew Karnitschnig
Headlines.Headline: Bunge to Buy Corn Products

PARAGRAPH.#text: Bunge agreed to buy Corn Products for $4.4 billion in stock, a sign global food demand is driving big agriculture to look for increased scale.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Bunge to Buy Corn Products
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Matthew Karnitschnig
Headlines.Headline: Selling at $50, Then $65 Is Bid

PARAGRAPH.#text: As Anheuser-Busch's directors weigh whether to sell the company to rival brewer InBev, there is only one question most shareholders want them to consider: Is $65 a share a fair price?

Headlines.Headline: Tiger's Injury May Hurt Brand, Too

PARAGRAPH.#text: While Tiger Woods' stature won't suffer during his injury layoff, there will be a temporary hit to the Tiger machine: TV ratings, attendance for PGA Tour events and corporate-hospitality sales all will suffer. Video

Headlines.Headline: St. Louis Stands by Busch

PARAGRAPH.#text: InBev hired a bevy of lobbyists, including the Breaux Lott Leadership Group, to help it overcome opposition to its $47 billion unsolicited takeover approach to Anheuser-Busch.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: St. Louis Stands by Busch
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: SIV's rescue may aid Goldman, but junior holders may get hurt

PARAGRAPH.#text: THE RESCUE of Cheyne Finance, an insolvent structured investment vehicle, conjures up something akin to nostalgia. First, because SIVs were one of the earliest casualties of the credit crunch. Second, because Goldman Sachs's plan to save this SIV recalls rather antiquated ideas of common sense and simplicity.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: SIV's rescue may aid Goldman, but junior holders may get hurt
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: InBev May Water Down Bud's Marketing

Headlines.BodyHeadline: InBev May Water Down Bud's Marketing

Headlines.Headline: Anheuser in Talks With Grupo Modelo

PARAGRAPH.#text: Anheuser-Busch has begun preliminary talks with Mexico's Grupo Modelo about a possible combination of the brewers that could help Anheuser thwart an unsolicited takeover bid by InBev.
